# Why This Works

Suppose

```text
a % k = r1
b % k = r2
```

Then

```text
(a+b)%k

=((a%k)+(b%k))%k

=(r1+r2)%k
```

To make the sum divisible by `k`

```text
(r1+r2)%k=0
```

So

```text
r2=(k-r1)%k
```

This mathematical property guarantees that every valid pair is counted exactly once.

---

# Edge Cases

### 1. Empty array

```text
[]
```

Answer

```text
0
```

---

### 2. Single element

```text
[5]
```

No pair exists.

---

### 3. All numbers divisible by k

```text
arr=[4,8,12]
k=4
```

Every pair is valid.

---

### 4. k = 1

Every number has remainder `0`.

Every pair is valid.

---

### 5. Even k

Need special handling for

```text
remainder = k/2
```

because it pairs with itself.

