# Interview Explanation (30–60 sec)

> "The brute-force solution checks every pair, which takes O(N²). A better approach is to use modulo arithmetic. Two numbers form a valid pair if the sum of their remainders modulo `k` is `0`. We can either count the frequency of each remainder and compute complementary pairs in O(N + K), or process the array in one pass using a hash map. In the one-pass approach, each number checks how many previously seen numbers were waiting for its remainder, adds that count to the answer, and then records the complementary remainder needed for future numbers. This gives an O(N) time solution with O(K) extra space."

---

# Key Takeaways

* Use **modulo arithmetic** instead of actual sums.
* Complement remainder is

```text
(k - remainder) % k
```

* HashMap gives a one-pass solution.
* Frequency array is easier to understand.
* Every valid pair is counted exactly once.

---

# Common Mistakes

❌ Checking every pair (`O(N²)`).

❌ Forgetting to use

```text
(k - rem) % k
```

instead of

```text
k - rem
```

(Otherwise `rem = 0` is handled incorrectly.)

❌ Double-counting remainder pairs.

❌ Forgetting the special case when

```text
remainder = k/2
```

for even `k` in the frequency-array approach.

❌ Allocating a huge frequency array when `k` can be extremely large; in that case, prefer the hash map solution.

